Like for example the fact that Sandy Hook was a hoax to take our guns away. And the fact that the covid vaccine is a bioweapon designed for genocide. I care about true things that your establishment sources would never publish. Also sometimes I would share a story if it's extremely funny, especially if it's both political & funny. I generally don't share stories that are just about ordinary headlines like what you put in this study. I don't have enough motivation to share that type of thing. The motivation has to be really compelling. I don't know why so many surveys and studies are so concerned about what we share, but It has to be super important or super funny for me to share it. There seems to be a general presumption in the media and in academia that people are "expected to" share postings on social media. If you want to do an interesting survey, I suggest you do a survey on whether or not and why or why not do people share posts on social media. I have been a heavy user of social media for more than 20 years. I have never once shared a post with any of my friends or followers. I choose not to do that because I do not see it as my job to relay world news to people. That is the job of the news media. It is also not my job or inclination to advertise products or agendas by reposting references to them. I think there are a lot of people who feel the same way I do about sharing. We use social media to stay in touch or communicate about shared hobbies, ocupations or interests. If I started sharing news articles to my friends and followers, they would probably unfollow or defriend me. Thank you for allowing me to participate in this survey.

"Reddit.com" is not really a source - redditors generally post articles they find elsewhere, and it is THAT source that needs to be evaluated for accuracy.
